{"title_page": "Qunar", "text_new": "{{Infobox website\n| name     = Qunar.com\n| services = [[Online travel agency]]\n| founded  = {{start date and age|2005|05}}\n| website  = {{URL|http://www.qunar.com/}}\n}}\n'''Qunar.com''' is an [[online travel agency]] serving China. Qunar means \u201cwhere to go\u201d in [[Mandarin Chinese]].<ref name=ocean/> \n\n== Customer Complaints ==\nDuring the second quarter of 2018, Qunar accounted for 32.7% of the complaints among the Chinese travel industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sohu.com/a/108187297_239711|title=\u4eba\u6c11\u7f51\uff1a\u5728\u7ebf\u65c5\u6e38\u6295\u8bc9\u96c6\u4e2d\u5728\u643a\u7a0b\u548c\u53bb\u54ea\u513f|last=|first=|date=2016-07-29|website=www.sohu.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Qunar.com, surpassing Ctrip.com, became the online travel agency received the most complaints during the above season. \n\nThe complaint reached its highest point during the COVID-19 outbreak in China, when the Civil Aviation Administration of China issued a statement on its website on January 21, 2020, requiring  airlines and travel agencies should handle their refund requests free of charge for passengers who have already purchased flight tickets to or from Wuhan and wish to cancel their trip.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstraveller.com/business-travel/2020/01/22/airlines-and-train-operators-offer-refunds-for-wuhan-bound-services-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Airlines and train operators offer refunds for Wuhan-bound services amid coronavirus outbreak|last=|first=|date=|website=Business Traveller|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> Following the outbreak, many domestic airline and international airline cancelled their flights to/from or within China. \n\nSince January 21, the number of customer calls to Qunar has surged and the highest peak is nearly 25 times of a typical day's handling capacity. Recently, the Qunar website has been frequently complained by customers that the refund has not been received for more than 40 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.ifeng.com/c/7utDt0J3pR7|title=\u7528\u6237\u6295\u8bc9\u53bb\u54ea\u513f\u7f51\u9000\u7968\u6162 \u6574\u4e2a\u884c\u4e1a\u5728\u627f\u538b|last=|first=|date=|website=finance.ifeng.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> As of April 4, 2020, the complaints totals 28,713 on Black Cat (Hei Mao), a website by Sina for customers to file complaints, and nearly 9,650 complaint cases remain unsolved.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tousu.sina.com.cn/company/view/?couid=2282463075|title=\u53bb\u54ea\u513f\u7f51_\u9ed1\u732b\u6295\u8bc9_\u65b0\u6d6a\u7f51|last=|first=|date=|website=tousu.sina.com.cn|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> Most of the customers complaints focus on the topic of Qunar is not following the airline's policy and refuse to refund or change the plane tickets. Some customer reported that request to refund are denied without a reason being told, and others reported that even if a refund is granted, Qunar cannot guarantee when the refund will arrive to their bank accounts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://k.sina.com.cn/article_7304197019_1b35d339b02001rx35.html?cre=tianyi&mod=pcpager_focus&loc=1&r=9&rfunc=100&tj=none&tr=9|title=\u53bb\u54ea\u513f\u7f51\u906d\u6295\u8bc9\uff1a\u8d8540\u5929\u672a\u6536\u5230\u9000\u6b3e\uff0c\u9000\u7968\u8fd9\u4e48\u96be\uff1f{{!}}\u9000\u6b3e{{!}}\u5ba2\u670d\u4eba\u5458{{!}}\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e_\u65b0\u6d6a\u7f51|last=\u6d77\u62a5\u65b0\u95fb\u5ba2\u6237\u7aef|first=|date=2020-03-10|website=k.sina.com.cn|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> \n\n==History==\nThe website was founded in May 2005.\n\nIn 2011, [[Baidu]] acquired a majority interest in the company for $306 million.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-baidu/baidu-buys-qunar-to-boost-travel-search-idUSTRE75N2XR20110624 | title=Baidu buys Qunar to boost travel search | first=Lee Chyen | last=Yee | work=[[Reuters]] | date=June 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, the company listed its shares on the [[NASDAQ]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.techinasia.com/qunar-raises-167-million-dollars-then-stock-price-nearly-doubles | title=Baidu\u2019s travel site Qunar raises $167 million on US IPO debut, sees stock price nearly double | first=Steven | last=Millward | work=[[Tech in Asia]] | date=November 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Baidu sold its stake in the company to [[Trip.com Group]] (formerly Ctrip) for a stake in Trip.com Group.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://ir.baidu.com/news-releases/news-release-details/baidu-announces-share-exchange-transaction-ctrip | title=Baidu Announces Share Exchange Transaction with Ctrip | publisher=[[Baidu]] | date=October 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, the website was acquired by Ocean Management Holdings Limited.<ref name=ocean>{{cite press release | url=https://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2017/02/28/928936/0/en/Qunar-Announces-Completion-of-Merger.html | title=Qunar Announces Completion of Merger | publisher=[[PR Newswire]] | date=February 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n[[Category:2005 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:2013 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:2017 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Online travel agencies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox website\n| name     = Qunar.com\n| services = [[Online travel agency]]\n| founded  = {{start date and age|2005|05}}\n| website  = {{URL|http://www.qunar.com/}}\n}}\n'''Qunar.com''' is an [[online travel agency]] serving China. Qunar means \u201cwhere to go\u201d in [[Mandarin Chinese]].<ref name=ocean/> \n\n== Customer Complaints ==\nDuring the second quarter of 2018, Qunar accounted for 32.7% of the complaints among the Chinese travel industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sohu.com/a/108187297_239711|title=\u4eba\u6c11\u7f51\uff1a\u5728\u7ebf\u65c5\u6e38\u6295\u8bc9\u96c6\u4e2d\u5728\u643a\u7a0b\u548c\u53bb\u54ea\u513f|last=|first=|date=2016-07-29|website=www.sohu.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Qunar.com, surpassing Ctrip.com, became the online travel agency received the most complaints during the above season. \n\nThe complaint reached its highest point during the COVID-19 outbreak in China, when the Civil Aviation Administration of China issued a statement on its website on January 21, 2020, requiring  airlines and travel agencies should handle their refund requests free of charge for passengers who have already purchased flight tickets to or from Wuhan and wish to cancel their trip.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstraveller.com/business-travel/2020/01/22/airlines-and-train-operators-offer-refunds-for-wuhan-bound-services-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Airlines and train operators offer refunds for Wuhan-bound services amid coronavirus outbreak|last=|first=|date=|website=Business Traveller|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe website was founded in May 2005.\n\nIn 2011, [[Baidu]] acquired a majority interest in the company for $306 million.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-baidu/baidu-buys-qunar-to-boost-travel-search-idUSTRE75N2XR20110624 | title=Baidu buys Qunar to boost travel search | first=Lee Chyen | last=Yee | work=[[Reuters]] | date=June 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, the company listed its shares on the [[NASDAQ]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.techinasia.com/qunar-raises-167-million-dollars-then-stock-price-nearly-doubles | title=Baidu\u2019s travel site Qunar raises $167 million on US IPO debut, sees stock price nearly double | first=Steven | last=Millward | work=[[Tech in Asia]] | date=November 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Baidu sold its stake in the company to [[Trip.com Group]] (formerly Ctrip) for a stake in Trip.com Group.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://ir.baidu.com/news-releases/news-release-details/baidu-announces-share-exchange-transaction-ctrip | title=Baidu Announces Share Exchange Transaction with Ctrip | publisher=[[Baidu]] | date=October 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, the website was acquired by Ocean Management Holdings Limited.<ref name=ocean>{{cite press release | url=https://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2017/02/28/928936/0/en/Qunar-Announces-Completion-of-Merger.html | title=Qunar Announces Completion of Merger | publisher=[[PR Newswire]] | date=February 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n[[Category:2005 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:2013 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:2017 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Online travel agencies]]\n", "name_user": "Joeyespm163ac", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCustomer Complaints:more detail", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qunar"}
